### Equivariance / invariance proofs

#### a.3.1 Time-derivative of an O(3)-equivariant function

Let \(f:\mathcal{X}\times[0,1]\to\mathcal{Y}\) be a function that is equivariant to actions of the group \(O(3)\), such that \(\bm{R}\cdot f(\bm{x},t)=f(\bm{R}\cdot\bm{x},t),\forall\bm{R}\in O(3)\).

Proof sketchWe need to show that \(\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\big{(}f(\bm{R}\cdot\bm{x},t)\big{)}=\bm{R}\cdot \frac{\partial}{\partial t}\big{(}f(\bm{x},t)\big{)},\forall\bm{R}\in O(3)\) and \(\forall\bm{x}\in\mathcal{X}\).

\[\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\big{(}f(\bm{R}\cdot\bm{x},t)\big{)} =\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\big{(}\bm{R}\cdot f(\bm{x},t)\big{)},\] \[=\bm{R}\cdot\frac{\partial}{\partial t}\big{(}f(\bm{x},t)\big{)},\]

where the last equality follows by linearity.

#### a.3.2 Inverse of an O(3)-equivariant function

Let \(f:\mathcal{X}\to\mathcal{Y}\) be a function that (1) is equivariant to the action of the group \(O(3)\), and (2) admits an inverse \(f^{-1}:\mathcal{Y}\to\mathcal{X}\), then \(f^{-1}\) is also equivariant to the action of \(O(3)\).

Proof sketchWe need to show that \(f^{-1}\big{(}\bm{R}\cdot\bm{y}\big{)}=\bm{R}\cdot f^{-1}(\bm{y}),\,\forall \bm{R}\in O(3)\) and \(\forall\bm{y}\in\mathcal{Y}\).

Since \(f\) is invertible, we have that to any \(\bm{y}\in\mathcal{Y}\) corresponds a unique \(\bm{x}\in\mathcal{X}\), such that \(\bm{y}=f(\bm{x})\), and that \(f^{-1}(\bm{y})=f^{-1}(f(\bm{x}))=\bm{x}\). As \(f\) is equivariant to the action of \(O(3)\), we have that \(\bm{R}\cdot f(\bm{x})=f(\bm{R}\cdot\bm{x}),\forall\bm{R}\in O(3)\):

\[f^{-1}\big{(}\bm{R}\cdot\bm{y}\big{)} =f^{-1}\big{(}\bm{R}\cdot f(\bm{x})\big{)},\] \[=f^{-1}\big{(}f(\bm{R}\cdot\bm{x})\big{)},\] \[=\bm{R}\cdot\bm{x},\] \[=\bm{R}\cdot f^{-1}(\bm{y}).\]

