### Details about \(F_{\varphi}\)

#### a.5.1 Working in ambient space

In this section, we omit the invariant features, and consider that \(\bm{x},\bm{z}_{t},\bm{\varepsilon}\in\mathbb{R}^{M\times d}\) are all collections of vectors.

In opposition to the notations introduced in Section 3, we would like \(F_{\varphi}\) and \(\tilde{x}_{\theta}\) (which ultimately are neural networks) to operate in ambient space directly, i.e. on \(\bm{z}_{t},\bm{x},\bm{\varepsilon}\in R\) with \(R=\{\bm{v}\in\mathbb{R}^{M\times d}:\frac{1}{M}\sum_{i=1}^{M}\bm{v}_{i}=\bm{0}\}\), instead of \(\mathbb{R}^{(M-1)\times d}\) as initially presented. To do so, we use the results from Garcia Satorras et al. (2021) that showed that the Jacobian of the transformation \(F_{\varphi}\) can be computed in ambient space, for \(\bm{z}_{t}\) and \(\bm{\varepsilon}\) that live in the linear subspace \(R\), provided that the transformation \(F_{\varphi}\) (invertible with respect to \(\bm{\varepsilon}\)) leaves the center of mass of \(\bm{\varepsilon}\) unchanged.

Considering flat representations of \(\bm{z}_{t},\bm{x},\bm{\varepsilon}\in\mathbb{R}^{M\cdot d}\), the parameterization of \(F_{\varphi}\) introduced in Eqs. (6), (8) and (9) can be adapted as follows to achieve such property

\[F_{\varphi}(\bm{\varepsilon},t,\bm{x}) =\mu_{\varphi}(\bm{x},t)+U_{\varphi}(\bm{x},t)\bm{\varepsilon},\] (10) \[\mu_{\varphi}(\bm{x},t) =(\mathbb{I}_{M\cdot d}-\frac{1}{M}TT^{\top})\tilde{\mu}_{\varphi }(\bm{x},t)\] (11) \[U_{\varphi}(\bm{x},t) =(\mathbb{I}_{M\cdot d}-\frac{1}{M}TT^{\top})\tilde{U}_{\varphi} (\bm{x},t)+\frac{1}{M}TT^{\top},\] (12)

where \(T\in\mathbb{R}^{M\cdot d\times d}=[\mathbb{I}_{d},\mathbb{I}_{d},...]^{\top}\), and \(\frac{1}{M}TT^{\top}\) corresponds to the linear operator computing the center of mass. In Eq. (11), the unconstrained mean output \(\tilde{\mu}_{\varphi}(\bm{x},t)\) is simply projected onto the \(0\)-CoM subspace, thereby inducing no translation. In Eq. (12), the unconstrained output of \(\tilde{U}_{\varphi}(\bm{x},t)\) is first projected onto the \(0\)-CoM subspace, before being translated back to the initial center of mass.

With this adapted formulation, we need to be able to (1) compute the latent variable \(\bm{z}_{t}\) given \(\bm{\varepsilon}\), (2) evaluate the Jacobian of the transformation \(F_{\varphi}\), and (3) evaluate the inverse transformation \(F_{\varphi}^{-1}\).

Computing \(\bm{z}_{t}\) from \(\bm{\varepsilon}\)Given that \(\bm{\varepsilon}\in R\), obtaining \(\bm{z}_{t}\in R\) from \(\bm{\varepsilon}\) simply amounts to (1) computing \(\tilde{\bm{z}}_{t}=\tilde{\mu}_{\varphi}(\bm{x},t)+\tilde{U}_{\varphi}(\bm{x},t )\bm{\varepsilon}\), and then (2) removing the center of mass from \(\tilde{\bm{z}}_{t}\) - the second term in Eq. (12) induces no translation as \(\bm{\varepsilon}\in R\).

Computing \(|J_{F_{\varphi}}|\) and \(F_{\varphi}^{-1}\)In what follows, we shorten the notation, and denote \(U_{\varphi}(\bm{x},t)\) by \(U\) and \(\tilde{U}_{\varphi}(\bm{x},t)\) by \(\tilde{U}\). To leverage known identities, we start by reorganizing Eq. (12), as

\[U=\tilde{U}+\frac{1}{M}TT^{\top}(\mathbb{I}_{M\cdot d}-\tilde{U}).\] (13)

The Jacobian of \(F_{\varphi}\) is given by the determinant of \(U\), and the latter can be derived by leveraging the Matrix Determinant Lemma,

\[\det U =\det\tilde{U}\cdot\det\big{(}\mathbb{I}_{d}+\frac{1}{M}T^{\top} (\mathbb{I}_{M\cdot d}-\tilde{U})\tilde{U}^{-1}T\big{)},\] (14) \[=\det\tilde{U}\cdot\det\big{(}\mathbb{I}_{d}+\frac{1}{M}T^{\top} (\tilde{U}^{-1}-\mathbb{I}_{M\cdot d})T\big{)},\] (15) \[=\det\tilde{U}\cdot\det\big{(}\frac{1}{M}\sum_{m=1}^{M}(\tilde{U} ^{m})^{-1}\big{)},\] (16) \[=\det\tilde{U}\cdot\det V,\] (17) \[=\prod_{m=1}^{M}\det\tilde{U}^{m}\cdot\det V,\] (18)

where \(\tilde{U}^{m}\) denotes the \(m\)-th \(d\times d\)-block in \(\tilde{U}\), and \(V=\frac{1}{M}\sum_{m=1}^{M}(\tilde{U}^{m})^{-1}\) is a \(d\times d\)-matrix. Computing the Jacobian therefore amounts to compute the inverse of \(M\)\(d\times d\)-matrices and the determinant of \(M+1\)\(d\times d\)-matrices. In practice, \(d=3\) such that all computations can be performed in closed-form.

Regarding \(F_{\varphi}^{-1}\), we do not need to evaluate the inverse transformation itself, but instead evaluate \(\bm{\varepsilon}\) given \(\bm{z}_{t}\),

\[\bm{\varepsilon}=U^{-1}\big{(}\bm{z}_{t}-\mu(\bm{x},t)\big{)}.\]

The inverse \(U^{-1}\) can be obtained via the Woodbury matrix identity,

\[U^{-1} =\big{(}\tilde{U}+\frac{1}{M}TT^{\top}(\mathbb{I}_{M\cdot d}- \tilde{U})\big{)}^{-1},\] \[=\tilde{U}^{-1}-\frac{1}{M}\tilde{U}^{-1}TV^{-1}T^{\top}(\tilde{ U}^{-1}-\mathbb{I}_{M\cdot d}),\] \[=\tilde{U}^{-1}(\mathbb{I}_{M\cdot d}-C),\]

where \(V=\frac{1}{M}\sum_{m=1}^{M}(\tilde{U}^{m})^{-1}\) as previously defined in Eq. (18), and \(C=\frac{1}{M}TV^{-1}T^{\top}(\tilde{U}^{-1}-\mathbb{I}_{M\cdot d})\). Given the specific structure of \(C\), the computation of \(\bm{\varepsilon}\) can be simplified to

\[\bm{\varepsilon} =U^{-1}\tilde{\bm{z}}_{t},\] \[=\tilde{U}^{-1}(\mathbb{I}-C)\tilde{\bm{z}}_{t},\] \[=\tilde{U}^{-1}\big{[}\tilde{\bm{z}}_{t}-\bm{c}\big{]},\]

where \(\tilde{\bm{z}}=\big{(}\bm{z}_{t}-\mu(\bm{x},t)\big{)}\) and \(\bm{c}=C\tilde{\bm{z}}_{t}\) acts as a translation operator. We note that computing the inverse transformation requires to invert \(M+1\)\(d\times d\)-matrices, but as \(d=3\) in practice, all computations can be performed in closed-form.

#### a.5.2 Invariant features

For simplicity, we omitted in Section 3 and Appendix A.5.1 that molecules are described as tuples: \(\bm{x}=(\bm{r},\bm{h})\), as only \(\bm{r}\) transform under Euclidean transformations. For the invariant features \(\bm{h}\), we use the following parameterization

\[\mu_{\varphi}^{(h)}(\bm{x},t) =(1-t)\bm{h}+t\big{(}1-t\big{)}\bar{\mu}_{\varphi}^{(h)}(\bm{x},t),\] (19) \[\sigma_{\varphi}^{(h)}(\bm{x},t) =\delta^{1-t}\bar{\sigma}_{\varphi}(\bm{x},t)^{t(1-t)}.\] (20)

which ensures that \(\mu_{\varphi}^{(h)}(\bm{x},0)=\bm{h}\) and \(\sigma_{\varphi}^{(h)}(\bm{x},0)=\delta\); whereas \(\mu_{\varphi}^{(h)}(\bm{x},1)=\bm{0}\) and \(\sigma_{\varphi}^{(h)}(\bm{x},1)=\mathbb{I}\).

ImplementationAs described in the main text in Section 3.2, \(F_{\varphi}\) is implemented as a neural network with an architecture similar to that of the data point predictor \(\tilde{\bm{x}}_{\theta}(\bm{z}_{t},t)\), but with a specific readout layer that produces the outputs related to \(\bm{r}\) (\([\bar{\mu}_{\varphi}(\bm{x},t),\bar{\sigma}_{\varphi},\bar{U}_{\varphi}(\bm{x },t)]\)). Additionally, it produces \(\bar{\mu}_{\varphi}^{(h)}(\bm{x},t)\) and \(\bar{\sigma}_{\varphi}^{(h)}(\bm{x},t)\) as invariant outputs.

Inverse transformationThe logarithm of the determinant of the inverse transformation \(\log|J_{F}^{-1}|\) writes

\[\log|J_{F}^{-1}|=-\log|J_{F}|=-\underbrace{\sum_{i=1}^{M\times D }\sigma_{\varphi}^{(h),i}(\bm{x},t)}_{\text{invariant features}}-\underbrace{\sum_{i=m}^{M} \log\big{|}\det(U_{\varphi}^{m}(\bm{x},t))\big{|}-\log\det|V|}_{\text{vectorial features}},\] (21)

where \(V\) is defined as in Eq. (18).

